<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="370" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,841,1874]" box="[199,1026,949,974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,949,974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Description.</emphasis>
FEMALE (
<typeStatus box="[478,583,949,974]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">holotype</typeStatus>
). Body length 
<quantity box="[746,835,949,974]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.5 mm</quantity>
; LFW: 
<quantity box="[919,1022,950,974]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.72" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" unit="mm" value="3.72">3.72 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,841,1874]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis box="[199,263,985,1009]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Color</emphasis>
. Body black. Mandible, palpi, tip of clypeus, antennae castaneous. Metasomal segments black with castaneous borders. Leg bright castaneous with trochanter dark castaneous. Fore wing hyaline with veins light castaneous; stigma dark castaneous (
<figureCitation box="[562,627,1057,1082]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[180,1415,217,1808]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epyris loisae sp. nov. A. Lateral habitus, B. Dorsal habitus, C. Lateral detail of mesosoma, D. Head, E. Lateral view of head, F. Drawing of mandible, G. Pronotum, H. Mesoscutellum, and I. Dorsal view of metapectal-propodeal complex. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/257132/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
Fig. 
<number box="[614,627,1058,1082]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,841,1874]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis box="[199,260,1093,1117]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Head</emphasis>
. Hairy, shining surface strongly punctate with punctures deep, close together, irregularly spaced. Mandible with long setae, three teeth progressing larger posteriorly to anteriorly; lowest tooth largest and sharpened; middle tooth smaller but still sharpened; upper tooth round. Clypeus flattened apically, emarginate, with sharp median ridge and long setae. Eye small, LH 
<number box="[757,792,1201,1226]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="2.6">2.6</number>
× HE, with short, erect setae. Ratios of antennomeres 
<number box="[151,167,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="4.0">4</number>
: 
<number box="[171,211,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.4">1.4</number>
: 
<number box="[215,254,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.5">1.5</number>
: 
<number box="[258,296,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.3">1.3</number>
: 
<number box="[300,340,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.2">1.2</number>
: 
<number box="[344,384,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.2">1.2</number>
: 
<number box="[388,428,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.2">1.2</number>
: 
<number box="[432,472,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.2">1.2</number>
: 
<number box="[475,512,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.1">1.1</number>
: 
<number box="[516,553,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.1">1.1</number>
:1.0: 
<number box="[601,638,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.1">1.1</number>
: 
<number box="[642,681,1237,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.8">1.8</number>
. LH 1.0 × WH, HE 1.0 × OOL, WF 
<number box="[1088,1137,1238,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="2.28">2.28</number>
× WOT, POL 
<number box="[1301,1336,1238,1262]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.2">1.2</number>
× AOL.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,841,1874]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis box="[199,319,1274,1297]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Mesosoma</emphasis>
. Pronotal disc 
<number box="[490,525,1273,1298]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="0.6">0.6</number>
× as long as wide, sculptured in same manner as head. Mesoscutum coriaceous, 
<number box="[151,186,1309,1334]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.5">1.5</number>
× length of mesoscutellum with punctures only on posterior half; notaulus narrow anteriorly and divergent, broadening posteriorly and converging, each notaulus separated by 
<number box="[980,1015,1346,1370]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.1">1.1</number>
× posterior width. Mesoscutellum coriaceous with punctures and setae on lateral edges; scutellar pit large, subrectangular, each pit separated by 
<number box="[1379,1414,1382,1406]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="0.1">0.1</number>
× width and slanting from center posteriorly towards lateral margin. Dorsal view of metapectal-propodeal complex 
<number box="[151,200,1453,1478]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="0.67">0.67</number>
× as long as wide, strongly reticulated on shining surface; metapostnotal median carina and each metapostnotal propodeal suture reaching transverse posterior carina; strong paraspiracular carina present; posterolateral corner foveolate. Fore wing with transverse-median vein strongly arched, convex posteriorly, but not meeting anal vein.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,841,1874]" box="[199,1113,1597,1622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis box="[199,316,1598,1621]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Metasoma</emphasis>
. Petiolate and smooth; T 
<number box="[597,609,1598,1622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="3.0">3</number>
–T 
<number box="[642,655,1598,1622]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="7.0">7</number>
with sparse punctures, sparse pale setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="370" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,841,1874]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1633,1658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[329,484,1633,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loisae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[329,484,1633,1657]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">Epyris loisae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[499,596,1633,1658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[499,596,1633,1658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs most obviously from 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[961,1123,1633,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvimanus">
<emphasis box="[961,1123,1633,1657]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">E. fulvimanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the sculpturing of the propodeum. In 
<emphasis box="[332,497,1669,1693]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[332,493,1669,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvimanus">E. fulvimanus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the propodeum is smooth, as opposed to being strongly reticulate in 
<emphasis box="[1326,1436,1669,1693]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[1326,1432,1669,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loisae">E. loisae</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Additionally, the posterolateral corners are strongly foveolate in 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[881,980,1705,1729]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loisae">
<emphasis box="[881,980,1705,1729]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">E. loisae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Finally, in 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[1117,1272,1705,1729]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvimanus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1272,1705,1729]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">E. fulvimanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, only the tibia is castaneous, and the mesoscutum in 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[574,672,1741,1765]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loisae">
<emphasis box="[574,672,1741,1765]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">E. loisae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much longer, 
<number box="[857,892,1741,1766]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" value="1.5">1.5</number>
× the length of the mesoscutellum as opposed to being equal length in 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1832" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1832" box="[393,548,1777,1801]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Epyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fulvimanus">
<emphasis box="[393,548,1777,1801]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="370">E. fulvimanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1130,1813,1838]" pageId="2" pageNumber="370" type="etymology">
